The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into five
levels: level I or excellent (pollution reading: not exceeding 50),
level II or fairly good (pollution reading: 51 to 100), level III or
slightly polluted (pollution reading: 101 to 200), level IV or poor
(pollution reading: 201 to 300), and level V or hazardous (pollution
reading: over 301).
The 47 cities monitored by the center include the four municipalities
of Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing, provincial (or autonomous
regional) capitals, and major cities in economically developed coastal
areas, and tourist attractions.
